So this place came highly recommend by our friend. We ordered 2 curries and soup. the portions were very generous UNTIL we actually opened the containers. In each of the large containers of curry were FIVE PIECES OF CHICKEN!!!!! We are aware there is a meat shortage, that's why we did not order beef or pork, we were trying to be mindful and get a cheaper meat, but I'm sorry, I've never been so skimped out when I spent $40 with tip. When I've eaten at like China Dragon, theres so much chicken, we usually have left overs, and while I definitely don't expect that of other restaurants, FIVE medium sized chunks of chicken in a 16 oz container is really pretty bad. I thought the curry was good, the soup was good, but that was pretty ridiculous and left a bad impression on us, as new customers. I am half Thai, and have been looking for an authentic place close by to be a regular customer, but this was a bad first impression. We wish you and your business all the best, but come on, I can't pretend that this is ok!

Bodhi Thai is a Thai food restaurant in East Pilsen. It's a tiny shop with just wall seating for four. Because of that, most people order their Thai to go. A friendly woman takes your order and another goes to work creating your dish out in the open kitchen. As you wait, order a Thai iced tea (it's really good!).  I ordered the green chicken curry and it was perfectly spiced and tasty. It comes with rice. However, afterwards I had the worst food poisoning. I am hoping it was a mishap and the food at least was tasty!
Reliable and good Thai food in Pilsen. You can get better Thai elsewhere, but definitely not bad.

The only reason I go there is because it's close. It's always been serviceable but lately it's been terrible. The last straw was the Tom Yum soup with so much sugar it tasted like sweet tea and the pad see ew was swimming in oil with a pile of soggy old veggies on top. If the owner is letting non thai chefs cook the food then they should be trained to know how thai food should taste.

Firstly,  there was a medium to long curly hair in my food. I doubt they wear hair nets in that place. I order spicy beef pad Thai. There just wasn't enough love overall. Delivery took forever  (about an hour 20) Despite them being an 11 minute drive from me. I gave this place a chance & I don't think i will order from here again. I give it three stars because the food was warm and was packaged nicely. The flavor just wasn't there for me.

Two orders of extra spicy fried rice, one Basil fried rice, the other Thai. Both showed up rice, neither showed up fried, or spicy. Completely unseasoned. Not a drop of Chili oil, or Thai peppers(bird peppers) present in either. The Basil fried rice turned into a second Thai fried rice. Pad See Ew was not Pad See Ew, rather, it was served with Pad Thai noodles and traditional broccoli as opposed to a wide flat noodle and Chinese broccoli. At the time of writing this I can say that I have now given three extra chances to Bodhi Thai to step up their game without a negative review. Unfortunately the owners and their staff have begun to indicate that they no longer enjoy creating credible food.

My review is based on the many many many Thai places I've been to through out the Chicagoland area over the course of 20 years. Not only this but I've made a lot of these dishes myself.  To me the first thing I always check out from a new Thai place is the pad thai.  I am of course more than willing to come back again to see if perhaps this was just an off night.  But the pad thai was extremely bland. There is no sign of the quintessential pad thai sauce that gives it its flavor. In fact when I took it home I had to put in my own pad thai sauce which I keep a bottle of in my fridge.  Also the eggs were cooked separately which really you need to cook the egg in with the noodles it's part of getting the flavor to mingle in with everything else which just doesn't occur when you cook it separate.  I would highly recommend marinating the tofu a bit more possibly?  I'll admit the price is actually pretty nice but I would actually be willing to spend a dollar and a half more for a bit more taste.  I'm sure this place is probably fine with folks who don't have as much experience with Thai food but if you are a bit of a Thai food nerd you may find this place lacking in flavor.  It could have been enough night though? I think I will probably come back here at some point to check it out again and if it's gotten better I'll gladly edit my review. Because living in Pilsen it's the only Thai place around unless you go over to Chinatown.  So far though the best Thai places I've had are hands-down mostly on the north side.

By far THE BEST Thai restaurant in all of Chicago! Their food is made from the freshest ingredients by a seasoned chief. There menu is full of traditional Thai dishes as well as modern/contemporary dishes all made with passion and love all at a great price. The staff is extremely friendly and accommodating, they greeted me with a smile and sent me off smiling. I suggest everyone to eat here as there is always something great to eat at an affordable price. This location is carry out and delivery only but you can go to their Berwyn location and sit down in their beautiful and comfortable restaurant.
